rComments: With all the bad reviews, I still took my chances and stayed in her class. Boy do I regret it. Compared to all my other psych courses, I've felt like i've learned the least from this class. Exam questions are irrelevant and does not summarize the main topics discussed in lectures. She says she does not want to trick you but i've felt that all term.
teacherRatingTags: ['Test heavy', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Tough grader']

rComments: I'm not sure why there are so many bad reviews for this prof. I had her for PSYC14. All the exam questions were multiple choice. If you go through the textbook and follow her lectures, an A isn't impossible. Her lectures are fun to attend. I just like her personality when she lectures.

Worst professor, not there to teach or help you. How is she still teaching at this university? Her test are filled with useless questions such as "who wrote this study", followed by a list of similar names. How does that test my knowledge of the course content. Wants her class to be hard, so grades unfairly; 50% average on tests.

One of the worst professors i've had at UTSC (that's saying something). Very condescending / spiteful, not helpful when you ask questions & instead will belittle you. Her tests are riddled with questions not to test your knowledge but to test if you were listening in class to every detail.. Remembering the authors of a study doesn't test content.
Aweful prof! Doesnt explain concepts thoroughly at all, rambles on all day. would take again % says it all.

Professor Tran was one of the most challenging, and therefore, rewarding professors at UTSC in the Department of Psychology. Took a D-level course with her and was thoroughly fulfilled at her expecting the best from her students. Pushed me to work harder and produce better results. If you're trying to get by with uni easy, DO NOT pick her courses.

Prof Tran is able to make boring material entertaining enough to keep my attention, which is a plus. Unfortunately, she loses points for assigning a project to the class with unclear instructions and grading criteria. To do well in the class, attend all of the lectures. The book materials comprise only 30% (it says 50% in syllabus) of the tests.

By far the worst course/prof Ive taken at UTSC. The 2 assignments are extremely vague and unclear, the TAs do not provide useful feedback and spend too much time on irrelevant, small details. The final was very tough considering it consisted of large paragraph case studies. Did not effectively mark students knowledge/understanding of the course
teacherRatingTags: ['Participation matters', 'Tough grader', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: Her lectures were somewhat intresting and she was engaging. Her midterm was fair and she had a detailee rubric for the first assignment. But the final was extremely difficult - one of the hardest. The final assignment was confusing and the TAs did not provide much help. Tutorials were a waste of time. I learned nothing from this course. Stay away..
teacherRatingTags: ['Participation matters', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Tough grader']

rComments: Honestly, the "would take again" percentage says it all
don't take a course with her. go to st. george if you have to.
Unfair marker. Doesn't care about her students and is rude.
Rudest prof ever. She doesn't care about her students and literally gets angry if you disagree with her. Straight up inconsiderate. AVOID AT ALL COSTS

There are 2 assignments and 2 exams. The assignments are not well explained mainly because the TA's are not good at managing the course. The prof does not do a good job of explaining concepts good enough to do well in her exams. She needs to better prepare students for her exams. The exams are paragraph long questions and are quite tricky.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Test heavy', 'Tough grader']

rComments: She now teaches PSYC14 and has now made it much more harder to do well in this course. Her grading scheme is extremely unfair for the short answer portion of the exam. She is a good lecturer but when it comes to exams, it really brings your grades down.

Her lecture is Okay and the course itself is not boring. But her marking scheme is so bad and unfair. I actually do not know how she marked our work------we put great effort on it but the grade is so bad. Never take her course again.

Sisi Tran is the most volatile professor I've ever experienced. If the class doesn't laugh at her jokes, she considers that as being disengaged and takes it out on the class (not going through assignments, etc). She will have arguments with students in class if they bring up alternative views. Don't take her classes. The material itself was fine.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Lots of homework', 'Tough grader']

rComments: Her lectures and class experiments were fun. My assignment grades really dragged my confidence down.  When I emailed her about my grades, her response was disheartening. She kind of intimidates me. I wish she taught us how to write a research summary & proposal as it is a first for most students, and 80% of final mark was based on these two papers.
not an awful course, rather boring. wouldn't say it's a bird course (then again that's subjective), but it's not bad.

This prof. is really BAD. Grading criteria do not exist. It's completely based on whether she FEELS you deserve a certain grade or not. You receive the same grade as your group (which sucks) and her comments after the fact are vague and not in rubric. She is not poised, even though she preaches tonnes about it. Bad prof, just out of sheer principle

No mater what experience I had with her, I have to say her lectures were really really interesting and I really like that. However, she was extremely unfair even though she said she is fair. She made so many unrelated comments to our presentation e.g. she said we use blogs to support argument however that were  links I provide for photo reference

Her course topics are interesting and very discussion-based and she has a tendency to favor outspoken or obnoxious individuals in class. She has very high standards for presentations and assignments but her exams are fair and relatively easy if you study fully. Overall, she is engaging as a lecturer but is biased and judgmental as a person.

Her lectures are really interesting. But you have to beg her for help and she's an incredibly tough marker. Lots of reading and an assignment every week. On the plus side the class actually does make you a better critical thinker, its just that the mark kind of kills your gpa in your last year. Good luck.

BEWARE of Tran. She is an amazing lecturer (because she is interesting to listen to), BUT her exam marking schemes for short answer questions are unfair. She rushes through theory and spends majority of time on discussion (interesting, but never tested). She will never empathize with students when it comes to grades. You will need to work very hard

Horrible experience overall in this course. Too much work given and the marking scheme is ridiculously hard compared to other courses. This is the lowest mark I have received in university and would recommend that this class be taken with another prof if u want to save ur gpa. On the bright side, she is nice in person lol

I love her so much, amazing professor, she cares a lot about the teaching aspect of her career and is very helpful. her classes are NOT easy, however they are so interesting that you will do good as long as you pay attention and do what she asks for.  I believe she's my favourite prof at UTSC, and she's very very good looking!
she cares more than any other prof at utsc.  best class I ever took.
Love this class!  Prof. Tran is the best prof at UTSC!
Great class, very easy if you follow directions, am trying to get into her d-level class
Great lectures! Definitely going to take D-level courses with her! She shares a lot of interesting stories I can relate to.
great class--will try to take more with this professor
Very good professor. Easy to do well in class if you like social psychology.

This is a great class and a great way to finish college.  The papers and presentations seem easy at first but they are very tough, but she REALLY cares about seeing you do well.  Definitely take this class.

the in-class experiments are pretty good and actually made research interesting to me.  Just make sure you listen to Prof. Tran and not the TA.  If you listen and follow the rubric of the paper, it's straightforward and a great class.
not an easy class--LOTS of writing that seems easy but isn't.  but she gives lots of comments to help.  i'd agree--one of my top two classes i've taken.
Tran really made this class interesting.  It's a class everyone in psych should take.
the best prof i have had at UTSC.  She cares a lot about students and gives lots of help and makes every class interesting.
Good lecturer. Fair exams.
